The $\mathrm{CH}$ stretching region exhibits significantly stronger signals due to the higher Raman scattering cross section of the $\mathrm{CH}$ groups and their higher amount. The previously discussed data suggested that the $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$ group of the cation forms a $\mathrm{H}$ bond with the $\mathrm{O}^{*}$ atom of the alkyl hydroxyl group of another cation. The other $\mathrm{CH}$ groups (neither aliphatic nor aromatic) Table 2. Observed Raman bands and their assignment: $(v w=$ very weak, $\mathrm{w}=$ weak, $\mathrm{m}=$ medium, $\mathrm{s}=$ strong, $\mathrm{sh}=$ shoulder, str $=$ stretch, $\mathrm{d}=$ deformation, bend = bending deformation, $\omega=$ wagging, $\rho=$ rocking, $s=$ symmetric, as =antisymmetric). A scaling factor of $0.9439$ was applied to the calculated wavenumbers in the $\mathrm{CH}$ stretching region.

