The detailed assignment of the $\mathrm{CH}$ bands is subject to an ongoing debate in the community. ${ }^{[59-62]}$ In the following, we use an assignment that is in concert with our previous studies. ${ }^{[26,63,64]}$ The assignments presented in the following are based on our previous work on imidazolium-based ionic liquids and the recent studies of two $\left[\mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{OHmim}\right]^{+}$-based $\mathrm{ILs}^{[65]}$ and an ammoniumbased picrate salt. ${ }^{[66]}$ The two high-wavenumber modes at 3151 and $3132 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ can be assigned to stretching vibrations of the $\mathrm{C}(4 / 5)-\mathrm{H}$ groups. They exhibit a slightly different frequency due to the fact that they experience a slightly different chemical environment within the crystal, as can be seen in Figure 3. The $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$ stretch is observed at lower wavenumber $\left(3106 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}\right)$ because of the hydrogen bonding interactions. These findings support the above discussion where we concluded that hydrogen bonding takes place between the $\mathrm{OH}$ and $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$ groups of the cations. Strong interactions between the cation $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$ and the anion $\mathrm{O}^{-}$, which were observed in 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazlium picrates, ${ }^{[47]}$ do not take place in $\mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{OHmimPic}$. The $\mathrm{C}(4 / 5)-\mathrm{H}$ vibrations, on the other hand, are influenced by electrostatic forces as well as indirectly through the $\pi-\pi$ stacking of the aromatic rings. The signatures between 3000 and $3100 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ are attributed to the two aromatic $\mathrm{CH}$ groups in the picrate anion, which is in good agreement with Raman data on other picrate compounds. ${ }^{[67]}$ In the range from 2800 to $3000 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$, the stretching modes of the aliphatic $\mathrm{CH}$ groups appear. There are two pairs of $\mathrm{CH}_{2}$ modes due to the fact that the two $\mathrm{CH}_{2}$ groups in the hydroxyethyl chain are chemically slightly different as one is neighboring an oxygen and the other one a nitrogen atom.

Further molecular information about both cation and anion can be obtained from the fingerprint region. In the experimental Raman spectrum, only a single $C=C$ band is found at $1566 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$. The shape of the band, however, is non-symmetric and reveals a weak shoulder at $1576 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$. The main band is likely originating from the picrate, while the shoulder can be assigned to the imidazolium cation. This is in agreement with the literature. ${ }^{[65,66]}$

The fingerprint region of Raman spectra has often been used to study conformational isomerism in imidazolium ILs, ${ }^{[22,68-71]}$ when alkyl chains with more than two carbon atoms are present. The majority of studies focused on butyl chains, which can exist in a trans and a gauche conformation. ${ }^{[72,73]}$ The bands between 600 and $650 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ have been identified as suitable markers for the conformation of the side chain. In butyl chains, a band at $\sim 625 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ indicates the trans conformation and a band at $\sim 603 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ is characteristic of the gauche isomer. In our experimental data, we observe a medium intensity band at $604 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ and a very weak band at $624 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$. The intensity of the $604 \mathrm{~cm}^{-1}$ line is more than a factor of ten stronger and hence it can be concluded that the hydroxyethyl group exists predominantly in the gauche conformation. This supports the results from the SCXRD and DFT investigations, where the data indicated that the hydroxyethyl group only exists as gauche conformer in the solid state (Figure 1 and 2). The weak trans signature observed in the Raman spectrum may be due to contributions from the surface or from defects inside the crystal.

\section{Conclusions}
In this paper, we have studied a hydroxyl functionalized imidazolium-picrate, namely 1-(2-hydroxyethyl)-3-methylimidazolium picrate $\left(\mathrm{C}_{2} \mathrm{OHmimPic}\right)$ by means of experiments and theoretical calculations. The aim was to investigate whether or not the structures theoretically predicted for isolated ion pairs and ion pair dimers can be found in the solid material at room temperature. It was shown that the commonly observed $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$-anion hydrogen bonding interactions do not take place. Instead, the hydroxyl group of the cation establishes a hydrogen bond with the picrate anion. When two ion pairs are close to each other, they establish a highly interesting pattern, which is dominated by cation-cation interactions: the hydroxyl oxygen atoms form $\mathrm{H}$-bonds with the $\mathrm{C}(2)-\mathrm{H}$ protons to give a distinct dimer. The hydrogen atoms of the $\mathrm{OH}$ groups continue to interact with the picrate anions. The resulting ion pair dimers have also been identified in the XRD experiments and where supported by the Raman data. In addition, two types of $\pi-\pi$ stacking interactions were observed in the crystalline material: $\pi-\pi$ stacking of two picrate rings (interaction distance $3.66 \AA$ ) and $\pi-\pi$ stacking between imidazolium cation rings at $3.69 \AA$ A. These arrangements result in a layered molecular structure of the crystal and promote the stability of the ion pair dimers. Evidence for such distinct ion pair dimers within a crystal lattice of a solidified ionic liquid has not been shown before, to the best of our knowledge. The applied analytical approach of combining DFT calculations of isolated ion pairs and dimers with experimental techniques providing chemical and vibrational structure has shown its great potential for stuyding the physical chemistry of complex materials.

